Food debt for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries in the euro area, prices were higher than expected in November - after 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been based on only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
Contrary to the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered leitzsins. It is estimated that the fall in interest rates would favour rising commodity prices and a slight fall in unemployment, leading to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least just below the two-percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is located in the Zwickmühle: inflation had to be "agreed" in order to exclude the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the euro area is responsible for rising food and energy prices.
The MATIF white notes rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also showed a significant price increase in 2007.
This year's world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts will expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
