In many places, disinfectants are not used
Today, more than a thousand infections were recorded in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overoccupancy of the beds, the overburden of the staff - all factors that are not exactly acceptable to the control of the infections, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
Disinfectants are also spared in many places.
A MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By December 10, 1094, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, according to the leading physician at the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of people in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as inflammation of the throat, mandelitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually react well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the means are administered too high or inadequately, antibiotics-resistant bacteria are produced from the well-responding bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weak, or permanently poor immune system, but also in the elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the day-to-day hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA warned that there is no place where it is not sought.
Resistance to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care professional wears rubber gloves and masks in the supply, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment," says Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA when entering the hospital, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample withdrawals too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable to curb the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and old age homes, the hospitals should investigate the patients who were admitted and isolate MRSA infected immediately.
However, microbiological sampling in Hungarian hospitals is not often practiced.
Last but not least, because there are no subsidies for this investigation from the State Health Insurance Agency.
Therefore, most cases would only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
On the European Union side, there are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological studies are necessary to prevent resistance to the agent, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Microbiological samples were even more rare among the ambulatory patients or those in primary care, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most frequently transferred from one patient to another by nursing staff.
This is precisely why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the home hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are narrowly intertwined, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 metres between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to point out, unfortunately, in the financially less well-set hospitals even there is a saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that directly favour the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent in these areas, or may stop the spread of the pathogen where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government Programme against MRSA
Taking control of MRSA infections causes the health insurances huge costs, so they are combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
