Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Minister of the Environment Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings on Tuesday end, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are advising on the Bali Roadmap, which sets emission reduction measures for the post-2012 period, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a intense debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already indicated that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue at the conference is whether the industrialised countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on support for developing countries.
The adjustment fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected to be read out at the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) as set out in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" would be successful or not. The Union would even be willing to use a 30% reduction if other major industrialized countries in the world, or developing countries, were also willing to fulfil their commitments in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, whereas the EU and its then 15 Member States had already committed themselves to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will meet quite well, as is to be read in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be concluded within two years, otherwise it would certainly enter into force only after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been underlined by the IPCC, the UN's International Nobel Peace Prize Scientific Committee on Climate Change, in its recent report.
This would slow down the reduction of emissions, and an increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, resulting in extremely serious and irreparable consequences according to scientists.
