Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August this year with the support of the "Move for a Better Hungary", have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the Institute's "Risiko-Warnings Report" states: "In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the exacerbation of existing ethnic tensions between the gypsy and non-gypsy populations in Hungary, which could lead to violent ethnic conflicts even in the short term".
The main reason for this is the Hungarian Guard's strategy, which is probably aimed at the provocation of such a conflict, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the politicians: "People of public life have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian concept".
It is assumed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least because of the enormous attention of the local and foreign media, "have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: Since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the rise continuously, so that since summer 2007 several organisations called "national self-defence associations" have been founded.
"These groups are common ground that they define themselves as a civil organization each time, openly boasting to prepare their members for their defence tasks, sometimes armed, (disaster protection, defence, orderly treatment), calling on the inability of the police, the army, or the state itself," it said.
And further on: All this is done in accordance with the method that tries to label different political aspirations as a bourgeois initiative based on the political and party dryness of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association are therefore not just intended to avoid legal obstacles that might arise as a result of the registration at court - it is at the same time a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months the Hungarian Guard has been quoted as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, as some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of its own anti-Hungarian policy.
All this has an impact on the region's political stability.
From the point of view of the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an individual phenomenon in Central-Eastern Europe, so the political risk for the whole region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose establishment was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
In the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard stood the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
BNU took the incidents immediately as a reason for the establishment of the National Guard, arguing that the aim of the organization was "national protection".
