In Hungary, holidays are regulated precisely by law, so that the practice of redistributing working days around the holidays has now established, but the coming year gives us less such days.
Also in the EU and in America you can understand something else under "Fair Day".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and job-free days.
Job-free days are mostly ecclesial holidays, or are related to significant historical events.
For example, we are celebrating New Year's Day: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone can rest the New Year's Eve celebrations.
We have a total of fourteen holidays all year round.
The state celebrations are the 15th of March, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the Memorial of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the foundation of the state, on May 1st, the work is celebrated, on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be completed, the Minister of Labour has for a long time been laid down in his own regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants.
Exceptions are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
This year the working order is only mixed up by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life in this country remains formal, since most take the special holiday for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve.
In the next year, there will be more holidays in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so that there will be fewer re-dispositions on working days than this year.
The calendar is first placed "on the head" around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday April 26th will be a working day so that Friday May 2nd will be a day of rest.
The second redisposition will be related to the holiday on October 23rd: On Saturday, October 18th, one will have to finish on Friday, October 24th in advance.
