A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian purpose, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. on request of a former victim or his family.
In May 2006, eleven states, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been in force since yesterday.
_Other Organiser
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to carry out research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of the forced workers, explains Reto Masters, director of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The detention lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were assembled for a practical reason after the war: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent staff work on tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, some of the scientific community has limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
We must not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, according to Dr. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
