A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk of Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe.
The majority of Russian exports of natural gas to the European Union (EU) is led by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit charges from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced supplies to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is taking place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in conversations," said Anatoli Kinakh, Ukraine's Minister of Economic Affairs of the Reuters News Agency.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit charges [to Western Europe] over Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a case of exports to Western Europe, which led to a dramatic rise in prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the largest gas deposits in the world, but much of this remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
