The Scottish State Health Service must improve controls of the criminal records of workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish public health service had no precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
However, his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly on a sample of five health authorities.
