It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out pre-employment checks to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The Chief Auditor's report now states, along with other recommendations, that the Executive Board should use guidelines on how to extract criminal records to help employers in controls in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some staff documents, these were not routinely carried out."
Black said that Scottish health authorities would follow their pre-employment investigation directives to a great extent, but added: "Our report identifies areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment investigations of potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that the NHS Scotland's current pre-employment tests work well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
