Venus is the closest planetary neighbor of the Earth.
The two worlds have about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but the Venus of the Sun is slightly closer.
Billions of years ago, scientists believe that Venus has had conditions that would have been very similar to those on earth and could even have been habitable today.
But because of the most unbroken carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotation speed, Venus began a completely different development course.
Today the planet is robbed of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which examined the plants for one year, provide a debilitating insight into how the Earth could develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of Venus Express Mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar."
"Our new data enable us to construct a scenario in which Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment."
