The pre-history is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, produced hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: these were (for reasons of cost) not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo Cardonagen factory.
They were not works of art, but their role models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes with the name "Typ Stockholm" rightly.
Some of them have scored more than $100,000 on auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 around one hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol was dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at Moderna Museet, studied three Swedish private property in addition to the six museum-owned Brillo boxes, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first founded and glazed, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
On the other hand, the structure of the copies from 1990 reveals that the colour was applied directly to the press panel with a paint roll without foundation - it is also not an oil but an acrylic color.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo Box," says Lars Nittve, Director of Moderna Museet: "If the "Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board" in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibitions."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow up on the "serious accusations" raised in the soap powder boxes.
But since then they have been covered in inexorable silence.
